description: Borrowed from French jet (“spurt”, literally “a throw”), from Old French get, giet, from Vulgar Latin *iectus, jectus, from Latin iactus (“a throwing, a throw”), from iacere (“to throw”). See abject, ejaculate, gist, jess, jut. Cognate with Spanish echar.

entries.meaning: Propelled by turbine engines.
A collimated stream, spurt or flow of liquid or gas from a pressurized container, an engine, etc.
A spout or nozzle for creating a jet of fluid.
(aviation) A type of airplane using jet engines rather than propellers.

definitionGroups.group: An engine that propels a vehicle using a stream of fluid as propulsion.

entries.meaning: A turbine.
A rocket engine.
A part of a carburetor that controls the amount of fuel mixed with the air.
(physics) A narrow cone of hadrons and other particles produced by the hadronization of a quark or gluon.
(dated) Drift; scope; range, as of an argument.
(printing, dated) The sprue of a type, which is broken from it when the type is cold.

verbs.description: jet (third-person singular simple present jets, present participle jetting, simple past and past participle jetted)

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To spray out of a container.
(transitive) To spray with liquid from a container.
examples: Farmers may either dip or jet sheep with chemicals.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To travel on a jet aircraft or otherwise by jet propulsion
(intransitive) To move (running, walking etc.) rapidly around
To shoot forward or out; to project; to jut out.
To strut; to walk with a lofty or haughty gait; to be insolent; to obtrude.
To jerk; to jolt; to be shaken.
examples: A Lady was wounded down the whole Length of the Forehead to the Nose  […]  It happened to her travelling in a Hackney-Coach, upon the jetting whereof she was thrown out of the hinder Seat against a Bar of Iron in the forepart of the Coach.

entries.meaning: To adjust the fuel to air ratio of a carburetor; to install or adjust a carburetor jet
(slang, intransitive) To leave; depart.

description: From Middle English get, geet, gete, from a northern form of Old French jayet, jaiet, gaiet, from Latin gagātēs, from Ancient Greek Γαγάτης (Gagátēs), from Γάγας (Gágas, “a town and river in Lycia”). Doublet of gagate.

adjectives.description: jet (comparative jetter or more jet, superlative jettest or most jet)

entries.meaning: Very dark black in colour.
(mineralogy) A hard, black form of coal, sometimes used in jewellery.
(color) The colour of jet coal, deep grey.
